,Recommended,422900,29513748,Posted: 26 January,all,Pathborn,"This is quite a weird game. There are certainly major issues: there's no mouseover help for much of the GUI, the GUI in general leaves much to be desired, new game elements are introduced too quickly (several each stage), the game itself is quite short, and the story not as good as Creeper World 3's, but in terms of weirdness there's something about this game that I liked.Perhaps it's just that nothing is really explained, there's a bunch of random jargon like redacted space that is never really cleared up, and most of the time that's annoying but here it's kind of superb in its relentlessness. In some ways confusion is the highest state of mind, because confusion creates and precedes curiosity, which creates and precedes knowledge. So, in effect, games that confuse the mind are the greatest games of all, and this game is certainly confusing.For instance, I beat the game, completed every story mission, and still feel like I don't know a thing about it. I can't even tell you if the game is well balanced or not because I often had no idea how I won, I was flying by the seat of my pants and I couldn't tell you what the difference between a Cruiser, a Destroyer, or a Joven ship is. I don't know if my strategy was any good, but my strategies did seem to eventually work, but they were probably nowhere near optimal. It's just a baffling, but interesting, game.Basically I'd give it a recommendation if you enjoyed Creeper World 3 and if you want a game that's basically like that, but has a less interesting story, but instead has much stranger and more confusing gameplay. If you haven't yet played that game by the same developer, do that first."
