,Not Recommended,422900,25861451,"Posted: 4 October, 2016",all,Mazian,"Without question, Knuckle Cracker produces interesting and innovative game styles. I absolutely loved Creeper World and Creeper World 3-- I bought the first game as a downloadable Flash game, and then jumped at CW3 when I saw it on Steam. If CW1 and CW2 were offered on Steam, I would buy them (CW1 again). The amount of content in CW3 was just amazing.The ideas behind PFE are a variation on the innovative CW game mechanics-- a procedurally generated enemy; game play where enemy behavior is emergent from the way you play. The rules are exceedingly simple, but the resultant behavior of the creep or particulate is really interesting.Unlike the CW series though (and especially CW3) the amount of game systems/content here is far below what I've come to expect from Knuckle Cracker.Other reviews have inspired me to add: CW included a creep depth mechanic and weapons that took advantage of that depth (Morters), there is no such depth mechanic in PFE. CW included anti creep and multiple bases and power sources could expand substantially. There is no such depth in weaponry or power sources in PFE. CW offered Titans, which were game changing. PFE offers no equivalent.As someone else noted, the tooltips and explanation of various ship modules is almost non-existant. The ship building could have been incorporated into the game play to add some really interesting gameplay opportunities-- the shipbuilding could have even been offered in the same way that map sharing is offered. The amount of additional content (a la extra missions in CW3) is virtually non-existant (by comparison.)As a simple idea: Create a point limit on the ships used in the campaign for each slot, and certain module requirements-- then filter the online database for ships that meet the point limit and module requirement-- then display options to the players of pre-made ships that they can select from-- or build your own.And I'm sure there are still yet other ideas that would have made the game way more interesting and compelling.Story has never been Virgil's strong suit, and yet PFE falls down more so than either CW2 or CW3.Instead, 16 missions with a storyline that is a variation of the rest of the CW world mythos-- A storyline that makes me think of ""The Matrix"" in space (or the SyFy series, Battlestar Gallactica.) ""All of this has happened before, and all of it will happen again."" Only the very existance of the particulate breaks the cycle, according to the story itself.I'm not totally against Knuckle Cracker, and while I would be more cautious next time I would still likely buy the next game... but I think the developer needs to remember to give care and feeding to that which earned the initial glowing reviews of Creeper World and put in the same kind of effort that went into CW2 and CW3.Final verdict: Wait until the game is on sale. (Or until Knuckle Cracker adds substantially more content.)"
