,Recommended,422900,29133619,Posted: 8 January,all,UniQMG◙,"tl;dr: Novel content that you absolutely need to try.It's basically your childhood dream in game form: Dynamic ships with volumetric, fully destructible hull which is simulated per-piece, no immersion-breaking health bars, only that giant hole in your ship which went straight through your lathe module. The enemy, despite being a mass of particles, is surprisingly relatable and seemingly intelligent (in the sense that you will rage at it because it destroyed your HQ while you were trying to hold it off elsewhere, or it managed to take out that mission-critical energy mine). There's also enemy ships with a rudimentry AI, but even those can be devasting opponents. Storyline is excellent and has ties with previous creeper world games, but you don't need those to enjoy this game.The game also includes a full ship editor, where you can build out your hull block-by-block then litter it with guns, energy tanks and support modules. There's also an in-depth mission editor with a fully-scriptable 'PRPL' module for creating complex custom maps with original behavior. If you're not one for building a map, there's a mission generator capable of making just about anything you want, and they play like an actual story mode mission, with a (normally) balanced progression, minus a few novelties usually present in most custom maps.Combat is surprisingly in-depth: Ramming with heavily armored ships works just as well as missile spam, and the hull+modules-to-build-time ratio really helps balance it as well. There's not a huge variety in weapons, but the ways in which you can combine those weapons lead to specialized ships and rich strategies. You can design a huge mothership with twenty of each module, but you need to defend it for a considerable amount of time due to the steadily increasing time-per-hull-cost ratio. Or you can go the route of several smaller ships, or even several ships which combine into a larger ship.The game isn't bad in terms of performance either: obviously, a massive particle simulation isn't exactly easy for your CPU but it runs fine on my mid-range gaming laptop. Graphics look great, although they're not as impressive as say, GSB2.All I can say is that this would be EPIC as a game engine for realtime player vs player ship combat. There's already fully-featured enemy ships controllable via scripting, but what could beat real multiplayer where you have to build your fleet up, organize your particulate and proceed to the all-out in a war of epic proportions.My only complain is that it would be nice if tankers would refuel ships within range of an energy mine if the mine was unable to provide them sufficient power.protip: Omnis (especially with the cannon and reactor upgrade) work great as both area denial/defense, stealth missions and cannon fodder."
76561198084707835,Recommended,422900,25959178,"Posted: 9 October, 2016",all,Argonwolf,"Rating: 9.5/10Particle Fleet is an amazing game in the classic style of Knuckle Cracker. Simple, colorful art, cheesy storylines and well-designed enemies. As with Creeper World 3 before it, Particle Fleet forces the player to fight a war on many fronts at once, all while managing logistics with a simple, intuitive energy transfer system.You have to be able to direct streams of particles, arrange land-capturing turrets for maximum effect, build walls, destroy enemy walls, destroy enemy plasma (slows you down if you try to drive through), repair your own plasma, take strategic energy points, attack structures (quite difficult since only one very short-ranged weapon can destroy enemy structures), manage a ragtag group of loose cannon particles who don't play by anyone's rules (emergent), construct and command a fleet of spaceships which you may have designed yourself, depending on your play preferences, and ultimately rid yourself of any particulate before moving to the next system to start the process again.Along the way you'll have to pick up info crates and blueprints for new ships (you can't build as many of each ship type as you want, you have to have a separate license for each one), and may be assisted by some very powerful capturable gun turrets. Or those turrets may belong to the particulate, and you have to withstand their withering rapid-fire barrages while shooting them with a mining laser. But it's all worth it when it turns around and fights for you in the end.One thing I particularly like is the Doppel. Doppels are adorable squishy conglomerations of jello cubes in the shape of spaceships that try to crash into you to do damage. They can also shoot particles at you. Despite the fact that the map editor lets you create friendly allied Doppel spawners, they don't feature in the campaign, which made me sad. You can't boss them around like normal ships, but their AI is usually enough to make them useful.Epic soundtrack makes you feel like you really are taking on the apocalypse itself and saving the universe. Thought it was worth mentioning.There are exactly two reasons why I am giving this game a 9/10 instead of a full 10/10.1: As of this review's writing, the map editor is extremely buggy, prone to crashing upon creation of a new map or locking the save/finalize buttons so you can't apply changes you've made. This is really frustrating because I like making maps and if I put a lot of work in to find that I can't save it, it pisses me off.2: The game ships with a custom procedural scripting language called PRPL (Particulate Reverse Polish Language, if the CW3 naming convention is continued here.) It's awesome because you can build your own custom objects in the game to do virtually anything, including new ship parts and enemy types. The documentation is still lacking, which is why I sort of dislike trying to make things with it. Of course it doesn't help that the language itself is the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ child of an object-oriented programming language and an assembly language, but hey it's not too difficult to learn so I won't give it too much crap.Other than that, good stuff. If you like real time tactics/strategy, you're liable to develop a crippling addiction to this game and you'll never regret a second of it.EDIT 1: I found prpl reference on the wiki. It may have been added recently or it might have been there the whole time (derp). Either way, I'm upping from 9 to 9.5. If Virgil continues to update this game like he has with his last game, I'll happily make it an official 10."
76561198036489070,Recommended,422900,33894753,Posted: 29 July,all,mikeday,"I loved the entire Creeper World trilogy so was interested to try this.  I had fun, but not nearly as much as with Creeper World.  In fact, it wasn't until several missions in that I actually started enjoying it.  Since I can't make a ""meh"" recommendation, I'm giving it a recommendation, just not a very strong one.  Here's some details:Pros:+ Clearly a lot of effort went into this.+ Can design your own ships.+ Good mix of different default ships with definite roles.+ Flexible tech upgrades - not locked into what you spend and can redistribute between general tech and specific ship boosts.  Can reallocate without loss, there's just a delay for full effectiveness.  This tech reallocation is actually one of my favorite features.+ Most missions do require some strategy.+ The particulate looks interesting.+ Sacrificing ships isn't a permanent loss and can be extremely useful.Cons:- Rather short.- First couple missions feel way too easy, as if you just need to move your fleet a few places and your ships do everything you need.- Did not really deliver on the ""Adaptive and Emergent"" claim made in the trailer - yeah the particulate did react a little bit, but never in a really surprising or interesting way, mainly just acting like it was magnetically attracted to ships or spawning a lot more when you get close to emitters.  Did not seem intelligent at all.The above are pro/con considering the game on its own merits.  But this game is part of the Creeper World universe, which begs a comparison with Creeper World 3 (the last and by far the best of the trilogy and an outstanding game in its own right).So Compared to CW3, Particle Fleet has the following Cons:- Music is not as good.- Interface feels less refined.  For example for some reason you can't view ship health in the normal lower box, where you can toggle all the ship features, there's a separate box for that.- Not as satisfying.- Not nearly as challenging.- Feels shorter.- Story isn't as compelling or interesting.So with all that, why am I giving this a ""Yes""?  Because its fairer than ""No.""  I did enjoy it, I don't feel ripped off or anything, and I want to encourage the developer to do better next time.  Creeper World 3 was awesome and I'm sure Knuckle Cracker will live up to it in future efforts."
76561198045209327,Recommended,422900,25776270,"Posted: 29 September, 2016",all,Rathian,"A delightfully addicting tower defense/real time strategy hybrid-esque game, with show-stealing enemy (and sometimes allied) particles that can freely bounce around the map or clump together in a variety of formations for more orderly assaults. Mix the gameplay with custom ships/units and new features and gimmicks being constantly introduced, and you have a game that rarely seems to get old. If you've played any of the Creeper World games, you'll feel right at home here. If not, go ahead and try it out!In addition, like the Creeper World games, Particle Fleet features a substantial custom level creator, complete with its own scripting system, which allows for the creation of some fairly elaborate levels, alongside a customizable random level generator. As such, there's tons of replay value, and there will be even more as the community begins to make more levels.The two weak points to me are really more nitpicking than anything. In the story mode, the grammar used by characters can be a little...off, sometimes. Nothing major, but it can be noticeable if you're the type to pick up on that. The other minor issue is that the music, while great and suitably epic feeling, tends to loop often enough to be noticeable. Once again, not a big deal.In conclusion, Particle Fleet is a fantastic game that I highly recommend to anyone with a taste for tower defense or RTS games, and it's definitely a more-than-worthy successor to the Creeper World series."
