,Recommended,422900,25785737,"Posted: 30 September, 2016",all,Vegaetalus,"If you enjoyed the Creeper World games, stop reading now and just buy this. The core gameplay is familiar and improved upon in several ways.This is one of those strategy games where you can sink your teeth into every mission and take things at your own pace (for the most part). I pause frequently during the gameplay to re-assess the situation and consider my next moves.I love that the map has so much going on, with all the particles floating about, but you don't really need to be aware of it all at once. You can take over the map one area at a time (depending on the size of your fleet and your tactical prowess).The game does have a slightly steeper learning curve than CW. You are given ships that contain modules that aren't fully explained in the tutorials. I recommend reading the Help in the main menu after playing a couple missions so you can digest everything that has been thrown at you."
,Recommended,422900,25774709,"Posted: 29 September, 2016",all,Carlz0r,"Similar to Creeper World in some ways, yet quite different enough to stand on its own.  If you're already a fan of Knuckle Cracker games, you'll feel right at home, without feeling like you're playing the same game again.  If you are new, it's time to get started!Added Oct 3, 2016:So I've been playing more.. I usually try to do a mission or two per day off, and I feel like that's a good pace to play at.I really love this game, and I think it has enough strategy and depth to keep me thinking, without being so complex that I lose track of things or find myself getting overwhelmed with features.The main game features a campaign with a number of scenarios that you must play in order.  If you're interested in the story, it will be slowly revealed over the course of these missions.  As you progress, you'll obtain more ships, 'omni' which are used to claim land for energy production, and new abilities.. such as being able to assign your 'amp gems' to overall buffs that increase your movement speed, energy efficiency, or add cannons and 'struc' walls to your stationary energy mines for defense, plus a lot more.Also, as you gain new abilities and expand your arsenal, the enemies will unveil new tricks of their sleeves.  It'd probably be best to leave much of this unspoiled, but I'll just say that simple floating red particles aren't your only concern, they're just kind of the main staple of the enemy forces later on.One of the coolest features, in my opinion, is revealed just a short time into the campaign.. friendly particle emitters, and the means to direct them.  These friendly particles can help you 'mire' land (the term for claiming the land, turning it blue, so it produces energy for you) and unmire the enemy land, harm enemy 'struc' walls and particles, give enemy weapons something to shoot at other than your ships, or even just bolster up your fleet from behind with a constant stream of good particles to help your fighting ships in combat.Another amazing feature is that the ships are made up of little grid-shaped pieces.  These pieces can be structural/defensive blocks, weapons, engines etc, and being hit by something will destroy these pieces.  Taking some structural damage will leave the vital parts functional, but vulnerable.. if the weapons or engines get hit directly, they'll be destroyed, and if the main 'core' of the ship gets hit, that ship will explode and need to reassemble it from scratch.  If your ship is within range of an energy source, however, it will simply use some of your energy to repair itself.Because of the way these ships are designed, you can use the in-game editor to create your own.  I haven't tested this feature much, but I believe user-made ships are restricted to non-campaign modes, such as user-created levels, and the randomly generated maps in the combat simulator.  I believe you CAN use these custom ships on campaign missions, but it will be in a sandbox mode, and only works on missions you have already beaten previously with the ships that are provided in the standard campaign mode.Anyway, I think this is my favorite Knuckle Cracker game.  I liked Creeper World 3 a lot, but eventually certain aspects of that game became too difficult for me, and it wasn't 100% my jam because it's kind of tower defense.  Particle Fleet feels a lot more like an RTS, the difficulty curve feels fair, and.. I just like it.  It's fun.  I would absolutely recommend this game."
,Recommended,422900,25776680,"Posted: 29 September, 2016",all,Master Derpy,"Can you make a bad game, please?I've gotten so used to developers putting out at least one pile of crap, that its really freaking me out you haven't done it yet. C'mon, just throw some half-finished fetus of a game out there. You're making the rest of the game industry look bad.For real though, a familiar graphical, retro feel. You can always tell who makes these games. Smooth, fun, decently written, well worth the price. As usual, I enjoy the hell out of it.Knuckle Cracker for life. Keep being you, homie, you're unstoppable."
