76561197971544967,Recommended,422900,29280692,Posted: 15 January,all,Blackblade,"Another excellcent game from this studio that's a little hard to classify.  It is different than the creeper world series but still feels familiar.  Instead of fighting creeper moving along the surface, you are fighting against particles that flow / shoot out of locations.  The particles travel through space based on the terrain, fields and natural forces.  There are also some other obstacles such as plasma (slows your ships), emergent (powerful somewhat random moving ship killers), mines, turrets and even enemy ships and ship like particles in latter missions.To battle this you have a small fleet and a limited land vechicle to fight this.  Each scenario defines what ships are available and each ship has a role (i.e. capturing spawn points, blocking/ramming, ranged fighting, killing ships, clearing plasma, speed, etc).  It makes for a very rewarding experience, slowly fighting back the particles and using your ships to the best of their abilities.  Very puzzle like and less RTS like.  It should also be mentioned you can build your own ships and use them in missions in sandbox mode or even make them the default ships in your own missions made with the editor.Overall I found this game easier than creeper world 3 (only creeper game I've played so far).  The story is also a bit on the short side but there are user made missions, hard missions and random missions which still gives a lot of content.  Overall, well worth your time if you are into unique strategy experiences."
76561197973589694,Not Recommended,422900,28871452,"Posted: 31 December, 2016",all,MightyFox,"Compared to it's predacessors, Particle Fleet is a dissapointment. There is very little strategy involved, the story is forced (painfully so), and the level variety leaves a lot to be desired. Every mission its the same thing. Turtle up in the energy well, capture more energy wells, make a massive fleet, destroy particle nodes. Rinse and repeat.Creeper world, the games predeccessor, had much more variety in terms of obsatcles and weapons the player was up against, and in response the player had to adapt. In Particle fleet, there is no adapting, because you are only allowed the ships you are given, and even the particles themselves don't really seem that dangerous when your ships can take a truckload of them inside your own energy wells. You can create a custom fleet, sure, but for most, that won't make the game any harder.As for the story, I don't mind so much its shorter than it's Creeper World counterparts. I do mind that it was poorly developed with an ending so forced only a ""first draft for sale on Amazon author"" would be proud of it. And before fan boys begin commenting ""well you only didn't like the ending because..."" No. That type of ending is fine so long as it is done right. This one isn't done right. It's pointless, senseless, and it practically gives a middle finger to the player. Perhaps I wouldn't have minded so much if the gameplay was interesting, but it wasn't.TLDR: In short it's Gun platforms vs. Particle effects, and that's it. Compared to Knuckle Cracker's earlier outings, this game just feels lazy and/or a cash in on an idea they were too far along to give up on but didn't want to take all the way. Knuckle Cracker games used to be a guaranteed purchase from me. After Particle Fleet, they arn't anymore."
